Comment: @greybeard Hi! Sorry for my ignorance, I was thinking about the question: what changed in the architecture of CPU in the past 5 years? I could not think of a better title.

Answer: \begin{blockquote}
Sorted - 0.549702s:

data, data + arraySize;
\end{blockquote}

\begin{code}
std::sort(data, data + arraySize);
\end{code}

That is called \em{destructive sorting}, it sorts by destroying the input array.

\begin{blockquote}
Unsorted - 0.546554s:

    // std::sort(data, data + arraySize);
\end{blockquote}

That is \em{non-destructive sorting}, it sorts without destroying the input array.

In the non-destructive sorting case, the source is still in-order. So no surprises. It depends on how well your CPU can do non-destructive sorting, but most likely, it is faster than doing destructive sorting.

Based on your test, it looks like you are on Ryzen, which has SSE4.1. AMD doesn't mention if a SSE4.1 optimisation exists for their version of `std::sort`, but the Intel implementation does. So it seems likely that the difference is due to a difference in the CPUs.

Or if there is an overload on `std::sort` that doesn't do destructive sorting, for some reason that does not return via `std::sort` correctly.

