Comment: Hi - just a small thing that didn't matter until now: If I wrap, let's say, `function delay(ms) { setTimeout(function() { sayHello('Alice'); }, ms); }` around `async function sayHello(name) { ... }` ... then my script looks like: `async function sayHello(name) { try { await delay(9999); } catch(err) { console.error(err); console.log('Hello, ' + name); } }` ... And if `await delay(9999)` (I.e. `await delay(7*maxPromiseDelay)`) then, at least so far the `console.log(name)` doesn't seem to execute ...

Comment: @user13882677 I think you need to await for the timeout - `async function sayHello(name) { try { await delay(9999); } catch(err) { ... } catch (err) { ... } }}`. You can't await async without it being true.

Comment: @VLAZ what do you mean when you say "if you want to be really paranoid ..." ?

Comment: @user13882677 I mean that you are unnecessarily complicating yourself (and your code). The solution is to declare the delay as synchronous function from the start, and the code you wrote in your question shows that the code can also be done purely with synchronous code.

Answer: The problem is you are waiting for the promise \strong{\em{after}} you've delayed it:

\begin{code}
   try {
        await delay(9999); // delay will finish, and then wait for async to be done
    } catch(err) {
        console.error(err); // wait for this too
        console.log('Hello, ' + name);
    }
\end{code}

[Try it online](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#)

You could await the delay promise with `async`:

\begin{code}
async function sayHello(name) {
    await delay(9999); // after delay finished, you await before calling sayHello
}
\end{code}

But you'd best pass the `delay` function to your 'syncTest':

\begin{code}
async function syncTest(delay = 0) {
    await delay(9999); // after delay finished, you await before calling async
    console.log('Hello, ' + name);
    sayHello(name); // sayHello is now also async (because of await)
}
\end{code}

[Try it online](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#)

Comment: Thank you so much ... that is a very elegant approach; I just needed to use the `await` in the 'syncTest' and pass the `async function` there. It is quite simple. :-)

Comment: @user13882677 you could pass a reference to delay rather than async, to make sure the callback gets invoked (if you use `async function delay(ms) { setTimeout(function () { sayHello('Alice'); }, ms); }`)

